title: chrono_harlaown
body:
A character in [[Mahou Shoujo Lyrical Nanoha]], one of the highest-ranked mages in the Time-Space Administration Bureau. Son of Admiral [[Lindy Harlaown]].

The Storage Device he used is called [[S2U]], and then he acquired another one in [[Mahou Shoujo Lyrical Nanoha A's|A's]] called [[Durandal_(nanoha)|]].

His seiyuu is [[Takahashi Mikako]] in the original series and [[Mahou Shoujo Lyrical Nanoha A's|A's]], and [[Sugita Tomokazu]] in [[Mahou Shoujo Lyrical Nanoha StrikerS|StrikerS]].

In the [[Triangle Heart 3 Lyrical Toy Box]] continuity, he was named Chrono Harvey and served an antagonistic role.

Carla, or [[Cara Cromwell]] (カーラ・クロムウェル) is a noble Vampire and the main antagonistic heroine of [[Cara The Blood Lord]]. She appears in the online games, [[Taimanin Asagi Kessen Arena]] and [[Taimanin RPGX]] and has been integrated into the mythology.
She is the vampire Queen of her own Kingdom but supports friendly relationships with humans and fights for justice. Carla is also part of the 9 Noble Demon Families and holds with that the title of Red Blood Lord (紅血卿).
Designed by [[kagami_hirotaka]]

title: a_nightmare_on_elm_street
body: A Nightmare on Elm Street is an American supernatural slasher media franchise consisting of nine films, a television series, novels, comic books, and various other media. The franchise began with the film A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984), written and directed by Wes Craven. The overall plot of the franchise centers around the fictional character [[freddy krueger|Fred "Freddy" Krueger]], the apparition of a former child killer who was burned alive by the vengeful parents of his victims, who returns from the grave to terrorize and kill the teenage residents of the fictional Springwood, Ohio in their dreams.

title: heather_mason
body: Heather Mason (ヘザー・メイソン, Hezā Meison) is a fictional character in [[Silent Hill (series)|]]. She is first introduced as a supporting character in the original Silent Hill (1999), and later returns as the main protagonist of [[Silent Hill 3]] (2003). She also appeared in [[Dead by Daylight]] (2020) as a playable character.

title: x_fingers
body:
A gesture in which the index fingers of both hands are crossed to form an X shape.

In Japanese body language, this means "no", "not allowed", or "bad", similar to [[X arms]]. Alternatively, it can indicate fighting or conflict. In a restaurant, this gesture is used to ask the server for the check.

Not to be confused with [[index fingers together]].

h4. See also

* [[crossed fingers]]
* [[X arms]]

title: citrus_(saburouta)
body:
A [[yuri]] manga series by the mangaka [[Saburouta]] and published in Comic Yuri Hime.

The series revolves around Aihara Yuzu, a trendy first year in high school who hangs out with her friends, attends mixers, and talks about boys. She ends up transferring to a very strict and prestigious all girl's school after her mother remarries and they move. At the new school, she finds herself at odds with the school rules and the student council president Aihara Mei.  After returning home she is caught off guard when Mei shows up at her home. As it turns out, Mei is her new younger step sister and they'll now be living together as a family.

title: disembodied_penis
body:
A [[penis]] that appears to be magically floating in midair, detached from any body.

Usually this is so an artist can draw a penis without having to draw a male body in the way of the female character.

For it to be a true disembodied penis, it can't just be that the body is [[out of frame]]. It has to either fade to nothingness at the base or be otherwise clearly detached.

h4. See also

* [[invisible penis]]
* [[disembodied hand]]
* [[disembodied tongue]]
* [[detachable penis]]

title: detachable_penis

title: good_girl_bad_girl
body:
[i]Good Girl Bad Girl[/i] is a brand created by Loter Inc. in 2005. The concept centers around an [[angel and devil]] couple of girls, one a blue themed proper person and the other a [[red skin]]ned trickster looking for fun. A pilot cartoon for the concept was considered, but never got off the ground.

In 2024, the concept blew up in popularity thanks to an old music video promoting the characters being shared on [[TikTok]].

body:
[b]Breath of Fire[/b] is a role-playing video game series developed by [[Capcom]]. It originated on the [[Super Nintendo]] Entertainment System in 1993. body:

title: impact_wrench
body:
An [b]impact wrench[/b] is a type of [[socket wrench]] [[power tool]] designed to deliver high torque, and are commonly powered either by compressed air or electricity.  It operates by rapidly rotating a mass to store energy and then suddenly delivering it to its output shaft. 

Impact wrenches are used in a wide variety of industries, such as automotive repair, heavy equipment maintenance, product assembly, and construction.  They're a standard equipment of race car pit crews, and allow them to rapidly switch out the car's tires in less than 20 seconds.

Impact wrenches are also called impactors, impact guns, air wrenches, or air guns.

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Impact wrench":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_wrench]

body:
A [b]brushcutter[/b] is a agricultural/[[power tool]] designed to trimming weeds, small trees, and foliage inaccessible to a [[lawnmower]]. 

It's composed of a long metal pole with handles usually around the middle, an engine/power pack located on one end and a metal mower blade or [[saw]] blade at the other end.  Also known as a brush saw or clearing saw.

title: power_drill
body:
A [b]power drill[/b] is a type of electric-powered, handheld [[power tool]] consisting of a handle bar with a trigger (similar to a handgun) that activates the device's motor when pressed.

Despite the name, modern power drills are not exclusively a [[drill]] as they are now designed to be modular, with the drill head can be swapped with various types of other heads for different purposes.

Not to be confused with [[impact wrench]], which has similar design but is otherwise a different type of tools.

title: phrygian_cap
body:
A soft conical cap, generally depicted with the top being pulled forward. Notably worn by [[Link]] and [[the Smurfs]].

Originally associated with several peoples from Eastern Europe during antiquity, it became a symbol of liberty over the century, notably in France where it is commonly associated with the [[French Revolution]].

Not to be mistaken with a [[nightcap]].

title: gale_(baldur's_gate)
body:
One of the eight Origin characters in [[Baldur's Gate 3]] who can either be the player character or potential party member. A male human wizard prodigy from Waterdeep, and romantically devoted to the goddess Mystra as her chosen. However, after letting his ambition get ahead of his better judgment, Gale suffered a deeply critical affliction and was spurned by Mystra, driving him to win back her affections at any cost. As a romantic at heart, Gale conducts himself as gentlemanly as possible and is considered to be one of the "good" aligned origins.

[spoilers]The affliction Gale suffers specifically is a Netherese Destruction Orb that has been implanted in his body, a result of him discovering a fragment of the Weave. In a bid to win back Mystra's attention, Gale took in the Weave with the belief that he could personally return it to her. His attempt failed, leaving him with this curse. If Gale doesn't keep this orb stable, it will explode with enough force to level a nation.

title: astarion
body: One of the eight Origin characters in [[Baldur's Gate 3]] who can either be the player character or potential party member. A male high elf rogue who was previously a magistrate of Baldur's Gate until the vampire Cazador took him, made him his spawn, and enslaved him for over a century. After the events of the start of game rendered him immune to the usual vampire weakness of sunlight and also breaking him free of Cazador's control, Astarion seeks to finally exact revenge against his former master. Hidden beneath a veneer of flamboyance and charm, Astarion is the most self-centered and callous of the Origin companions, generally preferring to not waste time on helping any unfortunate souls and even further toying with them just for the fun of it.

title: starry_moon
body:
A common error or stylization among scenery artists, where the [[moon]], usually in its [[crescent moon|crescent]] phase, is depicted as having stars inside its (obscured) radius rather than being drawn as a solid, spherical celestial body that occults the stars behind it.

Do not use this tag if the moon is depicted as an object rather than a satellite in space (for example, if a character is sitting inside the crescent moon).

title: demonion_ii:_maou_to_sannin_no_joou
body:
A 2014 [[eroge]] game by Astronauts/Sirius with illustrations by [[M&M]].

This is the sequel to Demonion. The nomadic people founded four countries on the once barren Nilt region. They were the [[elf|Elven]] kingdom of Lusario, the Eastern empire Shuka, the ice empire Kilos and the dark [[demon]] kingdom of Hados. However, Hados collapsed due to an instigated revolt by the humans. One hundred years later, the Diabolica were viewed as bringers of destruction and chaos, and as such, they were a target of discrimination and suppression.

[[Caym]] was a Diabolica [[prince]] who survived the fall of Hados in a remote place. A girl named [[Risbell]] visited him and pleaded for him to revive Hados to save the Diabolica, and to avenge the deaths of her parents by human hands. He proclaimed that he would defeat the three countries and make their respective queens his servants.

h4. Characters

* [[Caym]] (Protagonist)

title: ruger_mini-14
body:
An American .223 calibre/5.56×45mm NATO semi-automatic [[rifle]] produced by Sturm, Ruger and Co. Introduced in 1973, it was designed as a lightweight and rugged varmint [[gun|rifle]] for farmers and ranchers. It uses a Garand-style action with a short stroke, fixed piston, moving cylinder gas system. The [b]Mini-14[/b] resembles a scaled-down [[M14]] rifle.

Available in traditional one-piece wooden stock and [[folding stock]] with a pistol grip.

The Mini-30 is a variant that fires 7.62×39mm round.

h4. See also

title: soldier:_76_(overwatch)
body:
An offense-class character in [[Overwatch]].

Jack Morrison was a decorated soldier, and joined Overwatch with his best friend [[Reaper_(overwatch)|]]. After the Omnic Crisis, the position of strike commander was passed over Reyes and given to Morrison. This created a rift between the two men. At some point, Reyes led a rebellion against Morrison in the Overwatch headquarters, and an explosion took the two of them with it. Morrison eventually resurfaced as the vigilante Soldier: 76, now on a mission to expose the truth of Overwatch's collapse.

Has [[white hair]], a [[jacket]] with 76 emblazoned on the back, and a red [[visor]] on at all times.

Real Name: Jack Morrison

h4. Alternate Skins

title: tnt
body:
Shorthand for trinitrotoluene, an [[explosive]] compound primarily used for [[weapon|military purposes]] due to its high stability.

Contrary to popular belief, TNT is [b]not[/b] a general-purposes explosive that is widely used in the [[mining]] industry, due to their relatively low explosive yield and high cost compared to [[dynamite]]. The confusion stemmed from various American cartoons that often used the word "TNT" as a catchword for any type of explosives for the sake of simplicity.

For tagging purposes, the tag "TNT" should be used when the [[explosion|explosive]] material in question is clearly labelled as "TNT" or its alternate names. If not, tag it as [[dynamite]] (stick explosive) or another identifiable [[bomb|explosive]] type.

May be used with boxes of TNT or bundles/single sticks of dynamite labelled as TNT.

h4. See also

* [[C4]]
* [[TNT block (Minecraft)]]
* [[TNT (Crash Bandicoot)]]
* [[List of Weapons]]

title: landolt_c
body:
Also known as the Landolt ring. A ring with a small gap somewhere on it, giving the ring the look of the letter C.

This is utilized in a form of vision examination: Landolt Cs are arranged in rows with varying gap positions (usually the four cardinal directions, or the 45-degree placements between them), with each row getting progressively smaller. The person being examined must attempt to correctly state where each gap on the Landolt Cs can be found until a certain number of errors are made.

h4. See also

* [[Occluder]]
* [[Vision test]]
* [[Eye chart]]

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Landolt C":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landolt_C

title: gishki_emilia
body:
Daughter of [[Gishki Noellia]] in the [[Duel_Monster|Duel Terminal storyline]]. Turned into a spirit by her mother's rituals. Her body was turned into [[Evigishki Ghastkraken]] and her spirit turned into [[Evigishki Merrowgeist]]. Both were absorbed by [[Vylon Disigma]]. In an attempt at gettting her back, [[Gishki Avance]] attempted a ritual with the Photomirror, but that backfired, turning them into Evigishki Levianima. Noellia reversed the spell and gave up her life force in order to resurrect her daughter. Somehow alive, Noellia sacrificed herself to stop Evigishki Zielgigas.

After the war, Emilia and Avance formed the Nekroz tribe, with [[Shurit]] as their son.

h4. See also

* [[Dance Princess of the Nekroz]]
** [[Nekroz of Gungnir]]
** [[Nekroz of Sophia]]

title: white_horse
body:
[[Horse]] that its entire coat colour is white, may also include its [[mane]]. 

A white horse has mostly pink skin under its hair coat, and may have brown, blue, or hazel eyes. "True white" horses, especially those that carry one of the dominant white (W) genes, are rare. Most horses that are commonly referred to as "white" are actually "gray" horses whose hair coats are completely white.

h4. See also

* [[Sodashi (racehorse)|]] - A Japanese racehorse most noted for being the first white horse to win a Grade 1 race.

title: lu_meng
body:
[b]Lü Meng[/b] (呂蒙) (178 – January or February 220), courtesy name Ziming, was a Chinese military general and politician who served under the warlord [[Sun Quan]] during the late Eastern [[Han dynasty]] of China.

Early in his career, he fought in several battles under the banner of [[Sun Ce]], Sun Quan's elder brother and predecessor. Although he had been noted for his bravery, he was still deemed as nothing more than a "mere warrior" for his lack of literacy skills. Later, with encouragement from Sun Quan, Lü Meng took up scholarly pursuits to improve himself, gradually becoming a learned and competent military leader. In 217, he succeeded Lu Su as the frontline commander of Sun Quan's forces in Jing Province. Two years later, in a carefully calculated military operation, Lü Meng led an invasion of [[Liu Bei|Liu Bei's]] territories in southern Jing Province, swiftly and stealthily capturing all the lands from Liu Bei's general [[Guan Yu]], who was captured and executed after his defeat. Lü Meng enjoyed his finest hour after the victory but died a few months later because he was already seriously ill before the campaign.

h4. See also

* [[Romance of the Three Kingdoms]]

title: cara_(monster_musume)
body:
A [[Monster Musume no Iru Nichijou]] character. Cara (キャラ, Kyara) is a [[cow girl|female minotaur]], who works on the Black Lily Ranch.

Cara is a very [[tall female|tall]] (220 cm), [[dark-skinned female|dark-skinned woman]] with a [[huge breasts]] (L-cup) that [[breast expansion|grow]] even [[gigantic breasts|larger]] when full, as befitting a Milk Minotaur. Her B-W-H measurements are 122(L)-69-98. For being a descendant of Bullfighting Minotaurs, she is remarkably [[muscular female|muscular]]. Her hair is [[short hair|short]] and [[two-tone hair|dual colored]], [[white hair|white]] in the front and dark [[brown hair|brown]] in the back, and usually hangs loose. Her eyes are dark [[brown eyes|brown]].

As a Minotaur, she has a [[horizontal pupils]], pair of large upward-facing [[cow horns]] on her head, [[cow ears]], [[cow tail]], and a [[animal legs|cow legs]] (starting from [[knees]]) which are covered with fur and have [[hooves]] instead of feet.

h4. External links

* "Monster Musume Wiki: Cara":[https://dailylifewithamonstergirl.fandom.com/wiki/Cara]
other_names: キャラ(モンスター娘のいる日常)

title: itsuwa
body:
Itsuwa (五和) is a character introduced in [[ToAru Majutsu no Index: Old Testament]]. A seemingly shy girl of the Amakusa-Style Remix of Church at first, she later shows her mettle and effectiveness as an ally of [[Kamijou Touma]] (on which she has a notable crush).

Her name is derived from the real world town of Itsuwa in Kyūshū, which was later merged with other towns to form Amakusa City in 2006.

Itsuwa is described as a young Japanese girl with [[black hair|black]] [[medium hair]]. She wears her hair in a [[bob cut]] with short fringes. Kamijou Touma, upon first meeting her, references that she has double eyelids, the first feature he noticed on her.

Itsuwa has a [[large breasts]] but is referred by her Amakusa comrades as hidden. Her clothing consists of things that allows her blend with her surroundings more readily, such as her [[pink tank top]]-[[capris]] combo or her tank top over [[sweater]] with [[brown pants]] that seem to be cut apart. During her mission in Avignon, she was forced to wear skimpy clothing because she had nothing else to wear after jumping into the river to save Touma.

h4. External links

title: capital_ship_(eve_online)
body:
A type of [[spacecraft|spaceships]] from the [[EVE Online]].

Capital ships are the largest player-piloted ships in EVE. True capitals can only operate outside of high-sec space. While they can use stargates to travel (except to high-sec), they can also jump between star systems using built-in jump drives.
Most defensive and utility modules designed for subcapital ships can also be used on capital ships. However, certain capital-ship-sized modules can only be used on capital ships and some modules whose functions are unique to capital ships. The Capital Ship Modules page details these unique modules.
Capital ships are constructed from capital ship components, instead of materials.
All capital ships are immune to the Micro Jump Field Generator of Command [[Destroyer (EVE Online)|]]s.

h4. See also

* [[Super Capital ship (EVE Online)|]]

h4. External links

* https://wiki.eveuniversity.org/Capital_ships

title: danon_decile_(racehorse)
body:
[[Real Life]] Japanese racehorse. He initially gained notoriety after [[defecating]] mid-race (and winning) the Keisei Hai in 2024. After this victory, he headed on to the [[Satsuki Sho]], only for his jockey [[Yokoyama Norihiro]] to sense that the horse had gone lame at the last minute, having him scratched from the race to keep the lameness from getting worse.

In spite of what happened at the Satsuki Sho, Danon Decile was entered in to the [[Tokyo Yushun|Japanese Derby]] where, despite being the 9th favored to win, managed to beat the heavily favored Satsuki Sho winner Justin Milano.

title: antithetical_couplet
body:
In Chinese poetry, an antithetical couplet is a pair of lines of poetry which adhere to certain rules (see below). It is also called a [i]chunlian[/i], [i]duilian[/i] and [i]spring couplet[/i]. 

Outside of poems, they are usually seen on the sides of doors leading to people's homes or as hanging scrolls in an interior, and often during [[Chinese new year]] as a type of [[fai chun]] (festive decoration), expressing hope towards the new year.

title: ice_play
body:
A form of [[temperature play]], though not always strictly [[BDSM]]; it is also a form of foreplay when practiced to a less extreme degree. 

Common depictions involves running pieces of [[ice cube|ice]] across a person's exposed skin, or [[French kiss|French kissing]] while [[ice_cube_in_mouth|passing an ice cube]]. 

In more extreme cases, in which a [[BDSM]] tag would suffice, ice can also be used as an insertable. This is either for the [[vaginal_object_insertion|vagina]], [[anal_object_insertion|anus]], and occasionally for the male [[urethral_insertion|urethra]]. 

Ice play can be a risky practice, and as such, it can be considered a form of edgeplay; there are injury risks related to frostbite, hypothermia, and skin laceration.

To qualify as a dollhouse view, the items and characters inside the house should appear almost to be miniatures - a quick test is that nothing inside the building takes up more than 10% of the image. title: tionishia
body:
A [[Monster Musume no Iru Nichijou]] character.

Tionishia, or "Tio" for short, is an [[ogre]] and a member of the M.O.N., where she serves as the team's hostage escort/guard, due to her immense size and [[strong|strength]].

Tionishia is a very [[tall female|tall woman]] (227 cm) with [[dark-skinned female|dark skin]] and [[long hair|long]] flowing [[blonde hair]]. She has [[fangs]], [[pointy ears]] and [[huge breasts|breasts larger than her head]] (P-cup). Her B-W-H measurements are 160(P)-72-119. One of her most noticeable physical features is a [[single horn|single]] large dark [[red horns|red horn]] in her forehead, which connects directly to her skull.

She is one of the tallest characters in the series, easily dwarfing any human and most other Liminals. When on missions she wears a bulky suit of [[armor]], which covers everything except her horn. Because of her size, figure and horn, all of her clothes have to be custom-made.

Outside of her armour, when on duty, she wears the standard M.O.N. uniform, with a long yellow [[dress]]-[[robe]] under it.

h4. External links

* "Monster Musume Wiki: Tionishia":[https://dailylifewithamonstergirl.fandom.com/wiki/Tionishia]

title: xun_yu
body:
[b]Xun Yu[/b] (荀彧), courtesy name [b]Wenruo[/b] (文若), was a Chinese military official and politician who served as an adviser to the warlord [[Cao Cao]] during the [[Han Dynasty|late Eastern Han dynasty]] of [[Chinese Empire|China]]. 

Xun Yu was nominated as a xiaolian (civil service candidate) in 189 and began his career in the civil service. When the warlord [[Dong Zhuo]] seized control of the capital Luoyang, Xun Yu feared for his safety and resigned, returning to Ji Province. In the subsequent years, warlords quickly rose in each region; Xun Yu first served [[Yuan Shao]], whose power base was in Ji Province, but later left him and went to serve Cao Cao in 191. Cao Cao recognised Xun Yu's talent and he exclaimed, "Here comes my [[Zifang]]!" when Xun Yu arrived, and he appointed Xun as an army commandant. 

In 211, Xun Yu, whose ideals were for Cao Cao to continue being the protector of the Han dynasty, opposed a proposal by Dong Zhao for Cao Cao to set up his own self administrated feudal state within the Han Dynasty. Displeased, Cao Cao sent him an empty food box, a sign that he should commit suicide. Xun Yu died under suspicious circumstances of illness in Shouchun in 212.

h4. See also

* [[Romance of the Three Kingdoms]]

title: josef_mengele
body:
[b]Josef Rudolf Mengele[/b] (16 March 1911 – 7 February 1979), was a [[germany|German]] [[waffen-ss|SS]] [[officer]] and [[doctor|physician]] during [[World War II]]. He performed deadly experiments on prisoners at the [[Auschwitz]] II (Birkenau) [[concentration camp]] with his team of doctors. Well-known under the nickname "Angel of Death" ([i]Todesengel[/i]). 

Died in 1979 during hiding in [[Brazil]]. He had a [[heart attack]] while swimming near a beach.

title: teardrop
body:
A comical depiction of crying or tears. Very similar to [[sweatdrop]]. This tag is not meant to specify when there's one tear versus when there's more than one. Usually there is never more than one on a character's face.

Basically, teardrop is used when the tear is drawn on for comedic purposes, rather than to actually represent happiness/sadness/pain/pleasure/etc. They usually have a specific color, rather than being transparent like real tears, and are usually connected directly to the eyes. A teardrop may also accompany [[yawning]].

Rule of thumb: if the character appears to be actually crying, or the teardrop is transparent, it is usually [i]not[/i] a teardrop. For all other instances of shedding tears that don't properly meet the requirements for teardrop, use [[tears]] instead.

For non-comedic pictures with a single teardrop, use [[single tear]].

title: lagombi
body:
Lagombi (Urukususu in Japanese versions) is a Pelagus-class beast in the [[Monster Hunter (series)|]] series.

First appearing in [[Monster Hunter Portable 3rd]], Lagombi is a white-furred arctic mammal which looks like a cross between a [[rabbit]], a [[bear]], and a [[wombat]]. It has long black ears which gives it sensitive hearing, a rigid blue belly that lets it slide along frozen terrain like a [[penguin]], and sharp claws, which it can use hurl chunks of ice and slash at would-be hunters.

The creature's iconic ears also appear in [[lagombi (armor)|armors]] crafted from its hide.

title: troll_face
body:
An [[tag group:face tags|expression]] meant to elicit the same raging anger that its namesake activity causes. Usually portrayed as semicircular eyes (upper half exposed) and a [[smirk]] or open [[smile]], giving the impression that the person is almost goofily gloating about their victory over your sensibilities.

May also refer to a [[meme]]tic image from [[rage comic]] of a face with wide, annoying grin, to which the word "troll face" is nowadays associated with.

Not the same thing as [[doyagao]], which is a look of [[smug]] self-satisfaction at something impressive that's been done. Troll face is more a [[sneer]] of schadenfreude at something that's been done to another person. 

h4. See also

* [[doyagao]]
* [[Tag group:Face tags]]

title: flonne
body:
Flonne is an [[angel]] from the [[Disgaea]] series. She appears both in the first game and the second, often accompanied by [[Laharl]] and [[Etna (disgaea)|]]. She has waist length blonde hair, blue eyes, small angelic wings (or small demonic wings in some depictions, due to a certain ending in the first game) and a flat chest which gets her chastised every here and there in the first game.

As for her personality, she is a love freak, trying to prove that all demons have love within their heart. She is air headed, easily distracted, and often quite quirky. She is [i]usually[/i] against violence of any sort, though she became slightly more corrupt toward the end.

title: boobplate
body:
A [[breastplate]] (or similar piece of chest [[armor]]) with individually molded breast cups. Although more practical than [[bikini armor]] due to at least covering the skin, it would have the undesirable tendency to direct attacks into the wearer's sternum rather than deflecting them away like real armor.

This tag should [b]not[/b] be used for armor that would qualify as [[bikini armor]]. A boobplate should still cover a significant portion of the torso and not just the breasts. For armor that only covers the breasts and leaves most of the upper body exposed, use the [[bikini armor]] or [[chest guard]] tags instead.

Notable examples of characters who wear a boobplate include [[Darkness_(Konosuba)|]] from [[kono_subarashii_sekai_ni_shukufuku_wo!|Konosuba]], [[Catherine_(fire_emblem)|]] from [[Fire Emblem: Three Houses]], [[Noelle_(genshin_impact)|]] from [[Genshin Impact]], and [[Mash Kyrielight]] from [[Fate/Grand Order]].

title: cu_chulainn_(megami_tensei)
body:
A recurring Genma-race demon in the [[Shin Megami Tensei]] series. He is a depiction of the eponymous hero of Celtic mythology. His design is inspired by the 1978 manga Yousei Ou (Fairy King) depiction of Cu Chulainn.

His younger form is [[Setanta (megami tensei)|]] and his palette swap is [[Tam Lin (megami tensei)|]].

title: setanta_(megami_tensei)

He is a depiction of the mythical Cu Chulainn's younger self, before he slew the hound of Culann and still went by his birth name Setanta. In contrast to his older self he has [[short hair]], [[thigh boots]] and a distinctive [[plaid scarf]].

title: haneoka_school_uniform
body:
The [[school uniform|uniform]] of Haneoka Girls' High School in [[BanG Dream!]].

The [[winter uniform]] is a [[long sleeves|long-sleeved]] [[grey jacket|grey]] [[blazer]], a [[plaid skirt|plaid]] [[pleated skirt]], and a [[striped necktie]].

The [[summer uniform]] is a [[white shirt|white]] [[short sleeves|short-sleeved]] [[collared shirt]], with a [[striped necktie]], beige-yellow [[sweater vest]], and a [[pleated skirt]].

Neckties and skirts are color-coded by year. First-year students wear [[green skirt|green]], second-year students wear [[blue skirt]]s; and students of the Middle School branch wear [[purple skirt|purple]], with [[black jacket|black blazers]] in the winter.

title: ao_no_kanata_no_four_rhythm
body:
Visual Novel developed by sprite

An anime adaptation aired starting in January 2016.

h4. Plot

"In a world where flying is as simple as riding a bicycle, there is a popular sport called “Flying Circus.”

The [[Hinata Masaya|protagonist]] once had a bright future ahead of him in that field of sports but due to an overwhelming defeat in addition to a certain other reason, he has left that field.
However, he meets the transfer student [[Kurashina Asuka]] and regains his passion as he teaches her how to fly.

With his situation changed, he participates once again in the Flying Circus. Just how high will he be able to fly this time with Asuka at his side?

This is a love story about the two who met while soaring in the skies, and the friends surrounding them."

h4. External links

title: bousouzoku
body:
[b]Bousouzoku[/b] (暴走族, lit. "violent running gang") is a subculture of Japanese motorcycle gangs.

The stereotypical look consists of round or wrap-around [[sunglasses]], long [[hachimaki]] headbands with battle slogans, and a [[pompadour]] hairstyle.

Other styles consist of a military-styled [[school uniform]] (a [[gakuran]]) or [[jumpsuit]], with the gang's name on the back, and a [[sarashi]]. Usually, any oddities on a male's school uniform is a sign of gang activity or rebellion that falls into boso-style.

Their vehicle of choice is either a large [[motorcycle]], or a [[car]], both with extensive styling and modifications (such as [[neon lights]], low loading, etc.).

title: gloomy_bear
body:
The main character of [[Itazuraguma no Gloomy]]. A violent pink bear who was abandoned as a cub and adopted by a little boy named [[Pity (itazuraguma no gloomy)|]]. He began to attack his owner out of anger and eats humans. He is an allegory for the creator's belief that wild animals and humans are incompatible by nature.

Gloomy plushes have been made in other colors beside pink, but the character's canonical color is pink.

body:
2023 Italian war drama film about an episode of the Battle of the Atlantic, where the submarine the [i]Comandante Cappellini[/i] sunk the Belgian ship [i]Kabalo[/i]. Its commander [[Salvatore Todaro]] decided to disobey orders and to rescue the [i]Kabalo's [/i]crew, being forced to navigate on the surface for three days, making the ship an easy target for enemies. Pierfrancesco Favino plays Todaro in the film.

The [[comandante_cappellini_(kancolle)|submarine's personification]] from the game [i][[Kantai Collection]][/i] ""pitched in":[/media_assets/22492087]" to help promote the film's showing in Japan.

External links:
* "Wikipedia: Comandante (2023 film)":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comandante_(2023_film)]

title: charisma_house
body:
A Japanese multimedia project created by King Records under their EVIL LINE RECORDS label.

h4. Description
This is the Charisma House. Today, too, the charismatic men inside fixate solely on their own, unique Charisma.

However, they’ve yet to discover “True Charisma”. Therefore, these Charismatic men have temporarily come to live under the same roof, embracing their Charisma and nurturing it to new heights with each passing day. Surely there are those in this world who might laugh at them. However, they’re far too Charismatic to be affected. In fact, adversity becomes their fuel to further generate Charisma, allowing them to accumulate a splendid “Charisma Charge”. And awaiting once the Charge is full is…!?

An ordinary person simply couldn’t understand, but this is the story of the Charismatic.


h4. Characters
* [[Motohashi Iori]], the Charisma of Obedience
* [[Terra (charisma house)|]], the Charisma of Self-Love
* [[Kusanagi Rikai]], the Charisma of Order
* [[Sarukawa Kei]], the Charisma of Rebel
* [[Ohse Minato]], the Charisma of Internal Punishment
* [[Tendou Amahiko]], the Charisma of Sex
* [[Itou Fumiya]], the Charisma of Good and Evil

title: majin_buu
body:
[b]Majin Buu[/b] is one of the main antagonist from [[Dragon Ball]]. He is first introduced as the final antagonist of the original Dragon Ball manga and the [[Dragon Ball Z]] anime.

A genie-like magical life form created by the evil alien sorcerer Bibidi to conquer the Kais and thus to take over the universe, millions of years before the events of Dragon Ball take place. He was temporarily sealed away and brought to Earth; however, Bibidi was killed and Buu remained hidden. In [[Dragon Ball Z]], he's revived by Bibidi's son, [[Babidi]] in order to carry on his father's plan to conquer the entire universe.

Buu is known for having various different forms, the most notable ones being:
* [[Fat Buu]]
* [[Evil Buu]]
* [[Super Buu]]
* [[Kid Buu]]

h4. See also
* [[Female Majin]]
* [[Majin Android 21]]

title: genki_dama
body:
[b]Genki Dama[/b] (元気玉, literally [i]"Spirit Ball"[/i] but usually translated "[i]Spirit Bomb[/i]") is a special attack in [[Dragon Ball]].

To use the attack, the user [[arms up|raise their hands]] toward the sky, and gather energy (could be ambient energy or energy from people around the universe willing to give their spirit energy at the time of attack usage; the second usage is generally more well-known) to assemble a powerful [[energy ball]]. During this energy gathering phase, the user is vulnerable to all kinds of attacks from their enemy. However, the sheer potential of attack power made the ball an extremely powerful, if not an outright unstoppable, attack capable of defeating any opponents.

One of [[North Kaiou]]’s invented techniques, with the other one being the [[Kaiouken]].

title: synthwave
body:
A retro-styled music and art genre that grew in the 2010s.

The 1980s, [[wireframe]] 3DCG, purple, orange, [[sunset]]s, [[driving]] in a [[car]], [[palm tree]]s, huge [[building]]s, glaring logos, etc. are often used as motifs.

It is easy to get confused with [[vaporwave]] because it has some overlaps.

title: little_mac
body:
The playable character in most video games in the [[Punch-Out!!]] series. 

Little Mac is a [[boxer]] from [[New York City]]. Little Mac is short, 4' 8" to 5' 7" depending on the game, but is agile and quick and has won against boxing champions, such as [[Mike Tyson]]. [[Doc Louis]] is Little Mac's coach.

Little Mac appears in the [[Super Smash Bros.]] series, in the third installment as an [[assist trophy]], and in the fourth installment as a playable fighter.

title: ranbob
body:
Antagonist of [[Tales from the SMP]]: The Lost City of Mizu, played by [[Dream (youtuber)|]]. Hails from Mizu, an underwater city built in the same world as the Dream SMP several generations into the future. He is the descendant of [[Ranboo]] and the only surviving resident of the city until several fishermen show up through time travel shenanigans. [spoiler]He slowly picks them off one by one before revealing himself to be obsessed with his "idol", Dream, who he believes to have been completely morally correct in his actions and merely demonized by history.[/spoiler]

Like his ancestor, Ranbob is a part-[[Enderman]] hybrid, though he appears to be more Enderman than Ranboo is, given his uneven appearance. He has [[heterochromia]] (one [[purple eyes|purple]] and one [[yellow eyes|yellow]] eye) and wears a formal outfit with a black button-up [[vest]], a [[white ascot]] or [[collared shirt]], and black/grey [[vertical-striped pants]].

title: tales_from_the_smp
body:
Spinoff series of [[Dream SMP]] that showcases one-off characters in various points in time of the world's history. Each episode is mostly self-contained. Outside of worldbuilding, the primary connection to the main server is [[Karl Jacobs]], who stars as the series's time-travelling protagonist.

Some of the characters in episodes are related to main series characters or each other, such as [[Ranbob]] being the descendant of [[Ranboo]], and the characters George and Hamilton Billiam from "The Maze" being twin brothers who are related to previous TFTSMP antagonist [[Sir Billiam III]].

Would later be the basis for Karl's spiritual successor comic series "Time Traveler Tales", published by Dark Horse Comics.

title: slav_squatting
body:
A style of [[squatting]] where the [[pose]]r squats close to the ground, but with both heels planted instead of coming up.

Traditionally known in the West as "Asian squatting" until the 2010s, when it became increasingly associated with Slavs, most prominently the [[Russia]]ns, through whom, specifically the [[track suit]]-wearing [[gopnik|Gopniks]], the squat achieved [[meme]]dom, and thus most usually associated with online. 

In Japan, it is popularly associated with [[delinquent]]s, where it is known as "delinquent squatting" or "yankee squatting".

title: second_generation_enoshima
body:
A [[prototype design|scrapped design]] based on [[Enoshima Junko]] from the artbook for [[Danganronpa Another Episode: Ultra Despair Girls]]. She was originally planned to be a real character rather than just Monaca's "final goal".

Her first design is a black woman with large blonde [[afro puffs]], and besides this is otherwise identical to Junko in regards to personality and appearance. Her second design is described as being a crazy young girl who had the goal of taking over the Warriors of Hope.

It is a common misconception that she is a beta design for Junko, when she is actually a scrapped antagonist meant to be similar to her in-universe.

She is voiced by [[Akasaki Chinatsu]] in the anime adaptation.

title: unused_character_(kill_me_baby)
body:
A nameless, [[prototype design|unused character]] from [[Kill Me Baby]].

She is originally planned to be a rival of [[Goshiki Agiri]], but ended up being unused in the manga due to her planned comic relief role was already taken up by [[Oribe Yasuna]]. Despite this, she became popular after the release of the artbook, and would have a sporadic cameo roles in the anime adaptation. Because of this, she is generally considered "canon" by fans despite the lack of roles.

She has [[red hair|red]] [[medium hair]] and [[green eyes]] with a long [[braid]]. In her brief appearance in the anime, she is voiced by [[Kugimiya Rie]].

title: supergirl
body:
[b]Supergirl[/b], also known by her Kryptonian name as [b]Kara Zor-El[/b] is a character from [[DC Comics]]' [[Superman (series)|]] series. She is the young female counterpart of [[Superman]], usually having the same powers as he does.

There are many iterations of the character "Supergirl", but the most well-known and generally considered the "base" version is Kara Zor-El. She came from Argo City, which survived the destruction of her home planet Krypton but soon came to its own destruction. As Superman (Kal-El) is the last son of Krypton, then Supergirl, his cousin, is the last daughter of Krypton, with both coming from the same family house of El. She wears a female version of Superman's costume that usually gives her a [[skirt]] among other feminine alterations depending on her variation.

For an older female counterpart to Superman and her variations or costumes based on them, use the [[Superwoman]] tag.

h4. See Also
* [[Power Girl]]

title: windows_2000
body:
A version of [[Microsoft Windows]] released in 1999 as the professional counterpart to [[Windows ME]].

h4. Differences
* [[Windows 95]]
** Solid dark blue window border
** No extra taskbar icons
** Aqua default background
* [[Windows 98]]
** Blue gradient window border
** Email and [[Internet Explorer]] icons beside start button
** Aqua default background
* [b]Windows 2000[/b]
** Smoother gradient on window border
** Blue default background

title: monster_(manga)
body:
A seinen manga series by [[Urasawa Naoki]] and published by Shogakukan in [i]Big Comic Original[/i] from 1994 to 2001 and later adapted into a 74-episode 2004 anime series by Madhouse.

Dr. Tenma Kenzou was a highly-successful brain surgeon at the Eisler Memorial Hospital in Düsseldorf, East Germany, who was demoted for failing to operate on the city mayor (who later died) in exchange for saving Johan Liebert, a boy who suffered a bullet wound to the head during his parents' murder - only to find out, nine years later, that Johan turned into a psychopathic murderer responsible for the mysterious deaths of his superiors (which unprecedentedly re-promoted him as Head Surgeon). Tenma then went after him together with Johan's twin sister Anna, only to learn horrifying secrets concerning the "monster" he once saved.

h4. Main Characters:

* Dr. [[Tenma Kenzou]]
* [[Johan Liebert]]
* [[Anna Liebert]]
* Inspector [[Heinrich Lunge]]
* [[Dieter (monster)|]]
* [[Eva Heinemann]]
* Dr. [[Julius Reichwein]]
* [[Roberto (monster)|]]
* [[Wolfgang Grimmer]]
* [[The Magnificent Steiner]]
* [[The Monster Without a Name]]

title: x-men:_apocalypse
body: X-Men: Apocalypse is a 2016 American superhero film directed and produced by Bryan Singer and written by Simon Kinberg from a story by Singer, Kinberg, Michael Dougherty, and Dan Harris. The film is based on the fictional [[X-Men]] characters that appear in [[Marvel]] Comics. It is the sixth mainline installment in the [[X-Men film series]] and the ninth installment overall.

title: the_new_mutants
body: The New Mutants is a 2020 American superhero horror film based on the Marvel Comics team of the same name. It is a spin-off film in the [[X-Men film series]] and the thirteenth and final installment overall before the series moved to [[marvel Cinematic Universe |Marvel Studios]].

title: x-men:_days_of_future_past
body: X-Men: Days of Future Past is a 2014 superhero film directed and produced by Bryan Singer and written by Simon Kinberg. The film is based on the [[Marvel]] Comics superhero team The [[X-Men]], the fifth mainline installment of the [[X-Men film series]], a sequel to [[X-Men: The Last Stand]] (2006) and [[X-Men: First Class]] (2011), a follow-up to [[The Wolverine]] (2013), and the seventh installment overall. It stars an ensemble cast, including [[Hugh Jackman]], James McAvoy, [[Michael Fassbender]], Jennifer Lawrence, [[Halle Berry]], Anna Paquin, Elliot Page, Peter Dinklage, [[Ian McKellen]], and [[Patrick Stewart]] . The story, inspired by the 1981 Uncanny X-Men storyline "Days of Future Past" by Chris Claremont and John Byrne.

title: snoring
body:
The vibration of respiratory structures and the resulting sound due to obstructed air movement during breathing while [[sleeping]]. 

The sound may be quiet or loud. Snoring during [[sleeping|sleep]] may be a sign of possible obstructive [[sleeping|sleep]] apnea.

title: patio_umbrella
body:
A type of large [[umbrella]], similar to a [[beach umbrella]], primarily designed to provide shade but may also provide protection from the weather for outdoor deck and patio areas.  They often lack decoration and commonly are in a neutral color.  They feature a long shaft to tower above people and furniture, and are affixed either to a weighted stand or piece of furniture such as a patio [[table]] or [[lounge chair]].  Patio umbrellas may also feature a tilting mechanism to tilt the upper part of the umbrella to better block the sun.

Patio umbrellas are a common sight at [[pool]] sides and outdoor cafes.

h4. See also

* [[Beach umbrella]]

title: nanachi_(made_in_abyss)
body:
[b]Nanachi[/b] is one of the main characters appearing in [[Made in Abyss]], voiced by [[Izawa Shiori]].

Nanachi looks like an [[furry|anthropomorphic]] rabbit with goat-like [[horizontal pupils]] and a long tail. Often seen wearing a [[horned helmet]]. The [[white hair]] and [[yellow eyes]] are unchanged from the human form. 

Nanachi lives with [[Mitty (made_in_abyss)|]] in the abyss, and has a habit of saying "nna" (んなぁ) in their speech.

This character's gender is [[androgynous|ambiguous]], and should be tagged as [[1other]] unless depicted with definitive male or female features.

title: garfield_(character)
body: Created by Jim Davis and one of the most iconic comic strip characters in the West. Garfield is an orange, overweight tabby cat with an addiction to lasagna and a dry sense of humor. He is accompanied by his lonely owner, Jon Arbuckle, and a dog, Odie. In the late 2010s/early 2020s, various internet users would portray him as something significantly more eldritch, serving to perpetually torment Jon.

title: garfield
body:
Garfield is an American [[comic]] strip created by Jim Davis.

Originally published locally as Jon in 1976, then in nationwide syndication from 1978 as Garfield, it chronicles the life of the title character, [[Garfield (character)|]] the cat; [[Jon Arbuckle]], his human owner; and [[Odie (garfield)|]], the dog.

As of 2013, it was syndicated in roughly 2,580 newspapers and journals, and held the Guinness World Record for being the world's most widely syndicated comic strip.

title: queen_dizzy
body:
[[Dizzy_(guilty_gear)|]] after officially becoming the new Queen of Vialattea. At the end of [[Guilty Gear Strive]] Another Story DLC, Dizzy was shown revealing herself to the public. She no longer needs to hide away from the public, and is thus publicly recognized as the Queen of Vialattea. 

While Dizzy already made two appearances in Guilty Gear Strive’s main stories she only had a slightly altered version  of her [[Guilty Gear XRD]] design due to being non-playable. It wasn’t until July 21st 2024 that she would be announced as a playable character for the 4th Season Pass of Guilty Gear Strive. Notably being distinguished as  “Queen Dizzy” in both the teaser and the Official Website. 

The main difference of non-playable Dizzy and Queen Dizzy is the drastic differences in her designs. Naturally as the Queen of Vialattea Dizzy now wears a very regal outfit befitting of royalty, a brand new braided hairstyle, and even has a brand new design for [[Necro_(guilty_gear)|]] and [[Undine_(guilty_gear)|]]. 

As there are two versions of Dizzy depicted within Guilty Gear Strive it is only appropriate to use the this tag for the playable version of the character. Any depictions of Dizzy in her non-playable design even amongst other Guilty Gear Strive characters, should simply be tagged [[Dizzy_(guilty_gear)|]]

title: polishing
body: Using a cloth or [[cleaning rag]] to buff a dulled object to a shine.

title: wiping
body: Rubbing a damp or soiled surface by hand in order to [[cleaning|clean]] or [[drying|dry]] it. Usually involves an absorbent material such as a [[cleaning rag]] or [[tissue]].

title: detergent
body:
A chemical solution used for cleaning clothing or surfaces (such as mirrors or floors).

They usually come in liquid form and are contained in [[bottle|bottles]] (where you simply pour the solution out) or [[spray bottle]]s (self explanatory), though some may also come in powder form. 

Usually accompanied with a [[cleaning rag]] or [[towel]] for wiping the chemical on the surface being cleaned.

title: chaos_(dungeon_and_fighter)
body:
[[dungeon_and_fighter|Dungeon & Fighter]] character. Subclass of the [[knight_(dungeon_and_fighter)|Knight]]. Also known as the Demon Queen or Demon God.

Her "default appearance":[https://wiki.dfo.world/images/e/e0/Chaos_Full_Body.png] has her pink hair styled into twintails, [[head fins|fin ears]] and a purple [[heterochromia|left eye]]. Her outfit consists of a black leotard with red undergarments, asymmetric black gloves and leggings, and gold gauntlets and greaves.

As a "Demon God":[https://wiki.dfo.world/images/6/6f/Demon_God.png], she appears as a full-on [[demon_girl|demon girl]], with [[head_wings|wings on her head]] and [[low_wings|hips]], along with short black horns. Her hair is now worn loose, and she wears a black leather vest, torn black stockings, and black greaves and gauntlets.
